p to time, as the Romantics turn to the history of what might have been. In recounting Romanticism's interest in making things recurrently present, in recovering a past of what was close at hand yet underappreciated, William H. Galperin positions the Romantics as precursors to twentieth-century thinkers of the everyday, including Heidegger, Benjamin, Lefebvre, and Cavell. He attends to Romantic discourse that works at cross purposes with standard accounts of both Romanticism and Romantic subjectivity. Instead of individualizing or turning inward, the Romantics' own discourse depersonalizes or exhibits a confrontation with thing-ness and the material world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismx18th century. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aRomanticismxGreat BritainxGreat Britain. 0aRomanticismzGreat Britain. 4aemergence. 4ahistory. 4amissed opportunities. 4apossibility. 4aromanticism. 4athe everyday. 4athe now. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503603103zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503603103423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503603103.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles